DO you wash your hands properly?If you don’t, you could spread germs and illness.To stop poor hygiene spreading sickness, Cuticura urges Mzansi people to scrub their hands clean.if(typeof za24_DisplayAd != "undefined") za24_DisplayAd("300x250","2");<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a>Sithembile Mfayela, brand manager at Cuticura, said diarrhoea is serious.It responsible for over 1,5 million child deaths of under five year-olds per annum – and it is the second most common cause of child deaths worldwide. Sithembile said more education is needed to get people to wash their hands with soap, especially before eating or preparing food and after using the toilet.“Because diseases, infections and viruses are everywhere, hand-washing is very important.”Unicef has reported that hand-washing with soap is the most effective and affordable way to prevent diarrhoea and pneumonia.“Most people don’t understand the importance of cleaning their hands regularly and properly.“But it’s easy to see the link between major infections and illnesses, and a culture of not keeping our hands hygienically clean.”How to wash your hands- Wet your hands with warm, running water.- Apply the soap to the palm of one hand.- Rub your hands, palm-to-palm, for at least 30 seconds.- Run your fingers from one hand between the fingers of the other. Reverse the hands and repeat.- Don’t forget to rub the back of your hands and the tips of your fingers. Also check out your finger nails.- Rinse your hands and pat them dry with a clean towel.